typing%20lab.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3ESuccessful%20pitches%20should%20be%20brief%2C%20problem-focused%2C%20and%20tailored%20to%20your%20audience%2C%20she%20said.%3C%2Fli%3E%3Cli%3ELane%20advises%20being%20open%20to%20rejection%20and%20detaching%20ideas%20from%20your%20personal%20identity.%3C%2Fli%3E%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EJust%20over%20two%20and%20a%20half%20years%20ago%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcareer-pivot-google-ai-executive-mira-lane-2025-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3EMira%20Lane%3C%2Fa%3E%20was%20asked%20during%20an%20informal%20discussion%20with%20someone%20at%20Google%20what%20she%20wanted%20to%20do%20with%20her%20life.%20Unsure%20of%20how%20to%20respond%2C%20she%20said%2C%20%26quot%3BLet%20me%20get%20back%20to%20you%2C%26quot%3B%20and%20went%20home%20to%20think%20about%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EShe%20told%20Business%20Insider%20that%20she%20put%20together%20a%20%26quot%3Bone-pager%26quot%3B%20about%20an%20AI%20prototyping%20lab%20that%20explores%20the%20impact%20of%20tech%20innovation%20on%20society%2C%20and%20sent%20it%20to%20the%20Googler%20who%20would%20eventually%20become%20her%20boss.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20gamble%20paid%20off%20and%20she%20was%20brought%20on%20to%20spearhead%20Google's%20Envisioning%20Studio%2C%20an%20AI%20innovation%20prototyping%20lab%20made%20up%20of%20creative%20strategists%2C%20philosophers%2C%20and%20researchers%20dedicated%20to%20exploring%20technology%20at%20Google.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThough%20Lane's%20career%20transition%20appears%20seamless%20in%20retrospect%2C%20the%20vice%20president%20of%20Google's%20Tech%20and%20Society%20told%20Business%20Insider%20she%20has%20a%20long%20history%20of%20pitching%20new%20ideas.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20just%20have%20a%20bit%20of%20a%20scrappy%20history%20of%20starting%20things%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20are%20Lane's%20tips%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fhow-to-pitch-ideas-to-management-google-lens-creator-advice-2025-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22%5C%22%3Eon%20pitching%20ideas%20to%20management%3C%2Fa%3E%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%228ad6300f-e77c-45d3-8779-6d5759d30040%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EBe%20OK%20with%20'no'%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELane's%20first%20piece%20of%20advice%20is%20to%20get%20into%20a%20mindset%20where%20you%20feel%20OK%20with%20rejection.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BYou%20have%20to%20be%20willing%20to%20have%20people%20say%20'no'%20to%20you%20and%20be%20OK%20with%20that%2C%26quot%3B%20Lane%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Google%20executive%20said%20the%20idea%20you're%20pitching%20shouldn't%20be%20a%20%26quot%3Bpart%20of%20your%20identity%2C%26quot%3B%20but%20you%20should%20still%20be%20attached%20to%20it%20to%20some%20degree%20and%20believe%20in%20it.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20you%20really%20like%20your%20idea%2C%20you%20can%20have%20a%20bunch%20of%20people%20say%20'no'%20to%20it%2C%20and%20that's%20fine%2C%26quot%3B%20Lane%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%220e51e1b8-995e-43be-a960-bb3df91bd4b5%5C%22%3EMake%20it%20brief%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELane%20said%20that%20when%20she%20pitched%20the%20Envisioning%20Studio%20to%20Google%2C%20the%20document%20she%20created%20was%20about%20three-quarters%20of%20a%20page.%20She%20said%20she%20knew%20that%20the%20leader%20reading%20it%20wouldn't%20have%20time%20to%20read%20an%20essay%20or%20a%20slide%20deck%2C%20so%20she%20made%20sure%20the%20tone%20was%20direct%20and%20to%20the%20point.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELane%20said%20she%20wrote%20the%20shortest%20pitch%20possible%2C%20and%20sweated%20over%20%26quot%3Bevery%20single%20word%2C%26quot%3B%20to%20make%20sure%20each%20pushed%20her%20message%20forward.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BKnow%20the%20mindset%20that%20they're%20likely%20to%20be%20in%2C%20%26quot%3B%20said%20Lane%20and%20make%20sure%20to%20tailor%20your%20message.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%2244dc0c9b-a7d6-4516-8ce5-e134d7f8e781%5C%22%3EAnchor%20it%20in%20a%20problem%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELane%20said%20it's%20important%20to%20anchor%20your%20pitch%20into%20a%20problem%20%E2%80%94%20and%20that%20the%20problem%20has%20to%20be%20%26quot%3Bbig%20enough.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20she%20was%20pitching%20the%20Envisioning%20Studio%2C%20she%20said%20she%20felt%20like%20there%20was%20a%20societal%20issue%20where%20people%20were%20feeling%20like%20they%20didn't%20have%20control%20over%20the%20future%20of%20technology.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20has%20to%20be%20something%20that%20when%20people%20read%20it%2C%20they're%20like%2C%20'Yeah%2C%20I%20feel%20that%20problem%2C%20and%20it%20resonates%20in%20some%20way%2C'%26quot%3B%20Lane%20said.%20%26quot%3BIt%20can't%20be%20so%20abstract%2C%20or%20niche%2C%20where%20people%20are%20like%2C%20'well%2C%20that%20feels%20like%20a%20small%20thing.%20I%20don't%20know%20if%20I%20want%20to%20invest%20in%20it.'%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22beee293b-7104-4d89-9db4-a5817ea8be85%5C%22%3EKnow%20your%20audience%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3ELane%20said%20she%20usually%20pitches%20a%20solution%20that%20she%20knows%20people%20want%20or%20need.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20do%20a%20lot%20of%20research%20on%20the%20people%20I'm%20interacting%20with%2C%26quot%3B%20Lane%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELane%20said%20she%20was%20asked%20unusual%20questions%20in%20her%20Google%20interview%2C%20like%20about%20how%20she%20wants%20to%20make%20the%20world%20better.%20That%20gave%20her%20an%20idea%20of%20the%20kinds%20of%20questions%20executives%20were%20thinking%20about.%20She%20said%20others%20should%20aim%20to%20understand%20the%20audience%20they're%20pitching%20to%2C%20as%20well.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgoogle-studio-how-to-pitch-big-ideas-management-2025-8%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1754631781000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F68922464f748d8c055f6e6cd%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3